{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651266"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:21:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:21:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18440"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18440"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11158"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74712"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11158"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60195"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7729"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74712"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is studying genetic inheritance patterns in a population. Two unlinked genetic variants are being tracked. Variant A occurs in 25% of the population, and variant B occurs in 40% of the population.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the probability that an individual will have both variant A and variant B?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.10","0.40","0.32","0.15","0.65"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESince the genetic variants are unlinked (independent), the probability of both occurring together is calculated by multiplying their individual probabilities. This is known as the multiplication rule of probability. In this case:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EP(both variants) = P(variant A) \u00d7 P(variant B) = 0.25 \u00d7 0.40 = \u003Cstrong\u003E0.10\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The probability of independent events occurring together is calculated by multiplying their individual probabilities.","Independent events are those where the occurrence of one event does not affect the probability of the other event.","The multiplication rule of probability states that P(A and B) = P(A) \u00d7 P(B) for independent events."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60195"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18440"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60195"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T15:59:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T16:03:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11158"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74712"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emo